<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
Not evaluated (
<bibRefCitation author="Raimondo, D" journalOrPublisher="South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria," pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="23 - 35" refId="B24" refString="Raimondo, D, von Staden, L, Foden, W, Victor, JE, Helme, NA, Turner, RC, Kamundi, DA, Manyama, PA, 2009. Red List of South African Plants. Strelitzia 25. South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria, 86: 23 - 35" title="Red List of South African Plants. Strelitzia 25." volume="86" year="2009">Raimondo et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
Amongst the southern African species, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. amabile" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amabile">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. amabile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be confused with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. lanceolatum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanceolatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. lanceolatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to their small-sized nutlets (between 2-4
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-4) and flowers. However, the two species are easily distinguished by their flower colour (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. lanceolatum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanceolatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. lanceolatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has white corolla with blue throat, whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. amabile" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amabile">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. amabile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has bluish purple corolla). This species was also reported by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/4120226" author="Stapf, O" journalOrPublisher="Flora of China" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" refId="B30" refString="Stapf, O, Drummond, JR, 1906. Cynoglossum amabile, Stapf et Drummond. Bulletin of Miscellaneous Information, Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew. 1906: e202. https://doi.org/10.2307/4120226" title="Cynoglossum amabile, Stapf et Drummond. Bulletin of Miscellaneous Information, Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew. 1906: e 202." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/4120226" year="1906">Stapf and Drummond (1906)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.224.1.1" author="K ӧnig, J" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 28" refId="B18" refString="Kӧnig, J, Siwakoti, M, Hilger, HH, Weigend, M, 2015. A revision of the genus Cynoglossum L. (Boraginaceae Juss.) in Nepal and notes on the widespread Asian species. Phytotaxa 224 (1): 1 - 28, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.224.1.1" title="A revision of the genus Cynoglossum L. (Boraginaceae Juss.) in Nepal and notes on the widespread Asian species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.224.1.1" volume="224" year="2015">Kӧnig et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
to be like 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. furcatum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="furcatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. furcatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wallich (from Nepal, China, Bhutan, Vietnam, Thailand, Philippines, and India), based on flower and fruit size. The difference can be observed in the inflorescences, whereby 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. furcatum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="furcatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. furcatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a much larger plant with inflorescences up to 1 m tall, and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. amabile" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amabile">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. amabile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is up to 0.6 m tall.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stapf &amp; J. R. Drumm. in Bull. Misc. Inform., Roy. Bot. Gard., Kew 6: 202" authorityYear="1906" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum amabile" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amabile">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum amabile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in southern China where it is usually grown for ornamental purposes and naturalised in many parts of the world (
<bibRefCitation author="Xu, Q-J" journalOrPublisher=", Limited, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" refId="B37" refString="Xu, Q-J, Zhang, D-Z, Dang, L-J, Li, K-P, 2009. Triterpene acids from Cynoglossum amabile. Chemical Research in Chinese Universities 25(3): 404-406." title="Triterpene acids from Cynoglossum amabile. Chemical Research in Chinese Universities 25 (3): 404 - 406." year="2009">Xu et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Germishuizen, G" journalOrPublisher="Strelitzia" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="133 - 136" refId="B10" refString="Germishuizen, G, Meyer, NL, 2003. Plants of southern Africa: an annotated checklist. National Botanical Institute: Pretoria. Strelitzia 14: 133 - 136" title="Plants of southern Africa: an annotated checklist. National Botanical Institute: Pretoria." volume="14" year="2003">Germishuizen and Meyer (2003)</bibRefCitation>
, this species is only found in KwaZulu-Natal Province (Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Recorded distribution of Cynoglossum amabile in southern Africa based on the specimens examined." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.193.72270.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/658890" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">6</figureCitation>
), where it grows in open, disturbed sites, on gravel slopes and sandy, dry riverbanks.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/phytokeys.193.72270.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/658890" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" start="Figure 6" startId="F6">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Figure 6.</emphasis>
Recorded distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stapf &amp; J. R. Drumm. in Bull. Misc. Inform., Roy. Bot. Gard., Kew 6: 202" authorityYear="1906" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum amabile" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amabile">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum amabile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in southern Africa based on the specimens examined.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
