<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="taxonomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stapf &amp; J. R. Drumm. in Bull. Misc. Inform., Roy. Bot. Gard., Kew 6: 202" authorityYear="1906" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum amabile" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amabile">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum amabile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been described as a widespread species which grows in disturbed habitat and can be grown as an ornamental (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.224.1.1" author="K ӧnig, J" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 28" refId="B18" refString="Kӧnig, J, Siwakoti, M, Hilger, HH, Weigend, M, 2015. A revision of the genus Cynoglossum L. (Boraginaceae Juss.) in Nepal and notes on the widespread Asian species. Phytotaxa 224 (1): 1 - 28, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.224.1.1" title="A revision of the genus Cynoglossum L. (Boraginaceae Juss.) in Nepal and notes on the widespread Asian species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.224.1.1" volume="224" year="2015">Kӧnig et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). This species has only been collected once in South Africa by J. Stewart in 1977, since then there have been no later records or observations of this species in this region. Attempts to locate this species in the wild were futile. It is questionable whether this species occurs naturally in the southern African region since its single known locality is within a protected area in KwaZulu-Natal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
